ow gastrin levels","Low gastric acid with high gastrin levels","Normal gastric acid with high gastrin levels"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EType A chronic gastritis is characterised by autoimmune destruction of parietal cells in the gastric body and fundus. This leads to \u003Cstrong\u003Elow gastric acid with high gastrin levels\u003C/strong\u003E. The destruction of parietal cells leads to reduced acid production, which removes negative feedback on G cells, resulting in increased gastrin production\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe condition also leads to reduced intrinsic factor production, potentially causing pernicious anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Type A chronic gastritis primarily affects the gastric body/fundus leading to low acid and high gastrin levels due to loss of negative feedback.","Autoimmune destruction of parietal cells in type A gastritis leads to decreased intrinsic factor production and risk of pernicious anaemia."],"references":["Rugge, M., Sugano, K., Sacchi, D. et al. Gastritis: An Update in 2020. Curr Treat Options Gastro 18, 488\u2013503 (2020). https://doi.org/10.1007/s11938-020-00298-8","Sipponen P, Maaroos HI. Chronic gastritis. Scand J Gastroenterol. 2015 Jun;50(6):657-67. doi: 10.3109/00365521.2015.1019918. Epub 2015 Apr 22. PMID: 25901896; PMCID: PMC4673514.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51415"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15174"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51415"},"attributes":{"create